T1  - Reading Aparicio in Latinx/a/o studies: Toward remembering and re-imagining our academic location
AN  - 2404836313
AB  - In her pivotal and highly influential 1999 article “Reading the ‘Latino’ in Latino Studies: Toward Re-Imagining Our Academic Location,” Frances Aparicio insists that there are multifaceted ways of experiencing latinidad. She offered “a reading of both latino and latinidad as terms that carry with them a diverse array of competing authenticities or paradigms of identity that, together, and in conflict with each other, constitute the heterogeneous experiences of various Latino national groups” (Aparicio 1999, p. 10). As a graduate student, I was struck by that particular sentence, which inspired my first scholarly publication in 2001, “Colao Subjectivities: PortoMex and MexiRican Perspectives on Language and Identity,” and has continued to shape my research. “Colao Subjectivities” came to life as a seminar paper for one of Frances’s courses, The Politics of Language and Cultural Identity (Fall 1999), where I first read “Reading the ‘Latino’ in Latino Studies.” Most readers can detect Frances’s imprint in the essay, as well as that of sociologist Felix Padilla, and of cultural theorist Chabram-Dernersesian (1994). Some may perceive hints of Mexican American/Chicana writer Sandra Cisneros. But few, if any, imagine that the conceptual framework of “colao subjectivities”—the negotiation of multiple national-origin identities within the formation, modification, and performance of latinidades—is most indebted to the work of Puerto Rican poet Tato Laviera, specifcally the poem titled “café” (1985). This kind of epistemological foundation is signature Aparicio teaching and mentoring, a cultivation of interdisciplinarity that, I think, is often overlooked in “Reading the ‘Latino’ in Latino Studies.” More than offering a capacious conceptualization of latinidad, Frances taught her students that there are heterogeneous ways of studying latinidades. Engaging competing scholarly paradigms, approaches, and orientations “together, and in conflict with each other,” is the promise of Latino studies as a “central site for interdisciplinary work, collective projects, and for reconceptualizing the relationship between community and the production of knowledge” (Aparicio 1999, p. 4). This essay, “Reading Aparicio in Latinx/a/o Studies,” is as much a partial flashback to my intellectual formation as a Latinx/a/o studies scholar of Chicago latinidades, mentored and guided by Frances Aparicio and the collective projects she has engaged, as it is also a flash-forward to the kind of scholarship she continues to inspire and encourage in her students-turned-colegas. Sandra Cisneros’s collection of prose vignettes, The House on Mango Street (1984), and Felix Padilla’s sociological study, Latino Ethnic Consciousness (1985), bookend this tribute piece. As points of reference, they serve to reflect Frances’s interdisciplinary teaching. She used these two important texts to “underline some of the factors that created heterogeneous ways of experiencing Latinidad” through “inter-Latino dynamics,” “social and cultural interaction,” and circumstances that prompted calculated “political alliances” (Aparicio 1999, p. 9). The essay’s core, however, takes ups Frances’s appeal to scholars of latinidades for more historical research on how “diverse Latino groups have constituted particular cultural productions” that came to be associated with one national identity or a narrow notion of latinidad to illuminate various forms of “inter-Latino and inter-racial transculturations” (Aparicio 1999, pp. 9–10). Through an analysis of a little-known journal project, ECOS, published out of the University of Illinois Chicago (UIC) in the 1980s, I show how we scholars of Latinx/a/o studies are still catching up to what earlier complex visions of latinidades evoked and expressed in cultural practice (Aparicio 1999, p. 5).
